This process, however, of attaching all peregrini residing on Roman soil to the populus by the tie oi clientela could not be prolonged indefinitely. circumstances were gradually augmenting the number ol non-citizens so largely as to necessitate some new mode ol dealing with these classes. The military temper and strong organisation ol the Roman people resulted in a continuous addition ol territory to the domains ol the city ; little districts, principally oi Latin population, were constantly being annexed, and their villages razed, the inhabitants being encouraged to iloclr towards Rome, because thus they could be most easily cowed into obedience and hindered lrom rebellion. This was the population which became the plebs, and which played so important a part in the strictly legal, no less than in the constitutional‚ history oi Rome. The question how to deal with them became daily a more pressing political problem.
